You call both `assert(false)` (which compiles away in release) and `abort()` (which does not). Besides, again, you're trying to help me debug my application. I *want* my application in debug mode as I'm trying to debug it. I actually am running in RelWithDebInfo. I can't just build dlib as a .so in release anyway since I'm not linking in dlib since this is a template header-only library. So, are you telling me that I should compile my entire application in release mode? That's crazy. You're (in this context at least) a library author. Why do you feel compelled to put these type of constraints on your users, assuming they cannot recover from an error like this? You are not out of bounds, you are not in undefined behavior, you are not overflowing the stack, you are clearly handling this error--you're just choosing to use logic which ends my application to do it.

This is not hypothetical discussion BTW. The following is a snippet where I first ran into the problem, and what I had to do to avoid the problem. Another colleague asked what optimization lib I use, and I pointed him to dlib, but felt compelled to warn him about this poor design choice. In the following, both the number of parameters to be optimized, the starting values, and their search ranges are dynamically set by the user of the application.

```
// make sure our params, mins, and maxes all match up
if ( (m_optimizationParams.size() != m_optimizationParamsMax.size()) ||
     (m_optimizationParams.size() != m_optimizationParamsMin.size()) )
    throw( std::runtime_error("Number of params/min/max doesn't match up") );

// make sure the mins are less than the params
for ( uint ii(0) ; ii<m_optimizationParams.size() ; ++ii )
    if ( m_optimizationParams(ii) <= m_optimizationParamsMin(ii) )
        throw( std::runtime_error("The starting value cannot be less than the minimum value") );

// make sure the maxes are greater than the params
for ( uint ii(0) ; ii<m_optimizationParams.size() ; ++ii )
    if ( m_optimizationParams(ii) >= m_optimizationParamsMax(ii) )
        throw( std::runtime_error("The starting value cannot be greater than the maximum value") );
    
// run the optimizer
double rv(0.0);
if ( m_optimizationParams.size() == 1 )
{
    rv = dlib::find_min_single_variable(ErfSingle(m_params, erf),
                                        m_optimizationParams(0),
                                        m_optimizationParamsMin(0),
                                        m_optimizationParamsMax(0));
...
```

If everything is running either on the CPU or all on the GPU then there isn't any difference between host() and host_write_only().  So it's not a big deal in this case.

I'm still concerned about these split and cat functions.  It still seems like the code has indexing problems. The comments make it sound like the sample_offset is indexing into the k dimension (and therefore should be in the range 0 <= sample_offset < k()), but in the code sample_offset is just added to the pointer.  So it's just indexing the floats from the beginning of the tensor.  It would definitely be preferable that it be indexing along the k dimension :)

Also, I'm pretty sure you can implement this using the skip layers.  That way you wouldn't need to add a bunch of additional machinery to core.h, which is something I want to be as minimal as possible since it's full of a bunch of arcane template magic.  So for example, you should be able to do something like this:

template <typename SUBNET> using block1 = relu<con<5,3,3,1,1,SUBNET>>;
template <typename SUBNET> using block2 = relu<con<8,5,3,1,1,SUBNET>>;
template <typename SUBNET> using block3 = relu<con<20,5,3,1,1,SUBNET>>;

template <typename SUBNET> using inception = concat<tag1,tag2,tag3, tag1<block1<skip4< tag2<block2<skip4< tag3<block3<  tag4<SUBNET>>>>>>>>>>;

using net_type = inception<inception<inception<input<matrix<float>>>>>;

The only thing missing is a concat layer.  But that can be implemented by writing something conforming to the example layer interface defined in layers_abstract.h.  I put a lot of difficult template magic into core.h so that the layer interface could be as simple as possible :).   So you should be able to implement this using the easier interface :)

