This is indeed a known issue, one that our [documentation](http://docs.deis.io/en/latest/managing_deis/add_remove_host/#adding-a-node) doesn't seem to do a very good job of acknowledging or addressing yet - and I think that documentation is the thing we should likely address first. Apologies for that. There is no simple "fix" unfortunately, but the ideal way to manage the cluster would involve never using the disco url after the initial provisioning. One way forward for those who can afford to have a few extra nodes is to isolate the [etcd cluster](http://docs.deis.io/en/latest/managing_deis/isolating-etcd/), and leave the rest of the nodes as proxy nodes. The proxy nodes could then more safely be in an autoscale group. Still, even with an isolated etcd cluster, one would have to add and remove etcd member nodes in a manual fashion - creating the new nodes(s), using the member join api, then starting with the correct peers, or using static or dns based discovery. On AWS, or any other provider, nodes are cycled over time - and so any solution that assumes that nodes are permanent is flawed in this way.

In the meanwhile @szymonpk, I can gladly describe how to manually perform the process of managing the etcd cluster if it is helpful.

