@joguSD Yes. The `flush_amount` matches the maximum batch size imposed by Dynamo (which makes sense). However, when you're writing a large number of items this will end up triggering many `batch_write` calls back-to-back (i.e. every 25 items). Any unprocessed items will go right back into the buffer which gets written as part of the very next `batch_write` with no delay in between.

I don't think this is an edge case. Even [the example usage in the docs](https://github.com/boto/boto3/blob/develop/boto3/dynamodb/table.py#L44) writes 1 million items. Also, quoting from https://boto3.readthedocs.io/en/latest/guide/dynamodb.html#batch-writing:
> The batch writer is even able to handle a very large amount of writes to the table.

