I'm happy to help troubleshoot this, but I'm fairly certain it's not Curator to blame.

## Troubleshooting Steps
The fastest way to find an anomaly is to look at the `creation_date`.  For the following examples, substitute one of your suspect index names for INDEXNAME.

In Kibana in the Dev Tools console, or using `curl` or similar:

```
GET INDEXNAME/_settings
```
The result will show you:
```
{
  "INDEXNAME": {
    "settings": {
      "index": {
        "codec": "best_compression",
        "mapping": {
          "total_fields": {
            "limit": "10000"
          }
        },
        "refresh_interval": "5s",
        "number_of_shards": "1",
        "provided_name": "INDEXNAME",
        "creation_date": "1533630602162",
        "number_of_replicas": "1",
        "uuid": "ZxdRcRRcRwqX4GXnucyNww",
        "version": {
          "created": "6030199"
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```
The important line is `"creation_date": "1533630602162"`

Head on over to https://www.epochconverter.com/ and paste just the numeric value into the appropriate field, then click on "Timestamp to Human Date", and voila! You see the actual timestamp that the index was created.  I'm guessing that it isn't the same day as the the index, which is what you would have expected.  There are probably also very few documents in that index, too.  You can see exactly how many with:

```
GET _cat/indices/INDEXNAME?v
```
This yields a report like this:
```
health status index             uuid                   pri rep docs.count docs.deleted store.size pri.store.size
green  open   INDEXNAME         ZxdRcRRcRwqX4GXnucyNww   1   1    1346744            0      1.6gb            1gb
```

And finally, you can see some of what's inside by running:
```
POST INDEXNAME/_search
{
  "query": {
    "match_all": {}
  }
}
```
This will show you 10 documents from the index in the `hits` portion of the output (there may or may not even be 10).  You should see whatever is coming from Logstash at this point.

## Conclusion
The thing to remember is that Logstash is a stream processor.  It doesn't actually create indices in Elasticsearch.  It sends a bulk request that says, "please index this document/logline into the index named `logstash-YYYY.MM.dd`", and that date is derived from whatever the `@timestamp` field has for said document/logline.  **Elasticsearch will automatically create the index if it does not exist.**  Curator is, indeed, deleting these indices.  My guess is that you have some old files/data being re-read into Logstash, and the indices are being re-created.

Of course, there's always the possibility that it's something else. This is my first best guess, as I've seen it on many occasions.

