@bddppq @ezyang @dzhulgakov

One of the challenges with this is how much this wants to be integrated into the scheduler code. In my mind you could go one of two ways

1. Have an endpoint that when accessed, calculates/collects all the desired metrics and reports them back. In this case the endpoint would probably just get passed a reference to the scheduler, and it would go inspect `scheduler._state` and count various things.
2. Have the statistics being constantly collected and the endpoint simply reports back the collected metrics. This would require a persistent object of some sort to collect the metrics in and then add calls to the scheduler code to update various metrics as events happen.

A somewhat related choice, is if we would want to use Counters or Gauges for some of the metrics. Counters would mean that the metrics are collected over the lifetime of the central scheduler process, but you lose some information when you restart the server.

@colemanja91 Finding the right balance between metric names and labels is going to be interesting. I'd be tempted to have the task status be a label on the metric. I'd also fear that having the task family as a label would prove to be too high cardinality for effective use.

@Tarrasch I'm going to keep playing and maybe that will produce a draft PR of some sort. I definitely see there being an endpoint that exposes the metrics to what ever system wants to consume them. I'm not sure if it makes sense to add a tab to the visualizer, as I would expect the output to not be easily human readable. Or even if it is human readable the really interesting use is to see changes in the metrics over time. We'll see though.

